            {
              "id": "GodClass",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Possible God Class (WMC=245, ATFD=50, TCC=4.703%)"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nThe God Class rule detects the God Class design flaw using metrics. God classes do too many things,\nare very big and overly complex. They should be split apart to be more object-oriented.\nThe rule uses the detection strategy described in \"Object-Oriented Metrics in Practice\".\nThe violations are reported against the entire class.\n\nThe rule uses metrics to implement its detection strategy. The violation message\ngives information about the values of these metrics:\n* WMC: a class complexity measure, see {% jdoc java::lang.java.metrics.JavaMetrics#WEIGHED_METHOD_COUNT %}\n* ATFD: a measure of how much data external data the class uses, see {% jdoc java::lang.java.metrics.JavaMetrics#ACCESS_TO_FOREIGN_DATA %}\n* TCC: a measure of how tightly related the methods are, see {% jdoc java::lang.java.metrics.JavaMetrics#TIGHT_CLASS_COHESION %}\n\nThe rule identifies a god class by looking for classes which have all of the following properties:\n* High WMC\n* High ATFD\n* Low TCC\n\nSee also the reference:\n\nMichele Lanza and Radu Marinescu. *Object-Oriented Metrics in Practice:\nUsing Software Metrics to Characterize, Evaluate, and Improve the Design\nof Object-Oriented Systems.* Springer, Berlin, 1 edition, October 2006. Page 80.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_design.html#godclass",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nThe God Class rule detects the God Class design flaw using metrics. God classes do too many things,\nare very big and overly complex. They should be split apart to be more object-oriented.\nThe rule uses the detection strategy described in \"Object-Oriented Metrics in Practice\".\nThe violations are reported against the entire class.\n\nThe rule uses metrics to implement its detection strategy. The violation message\ngives information about the values of these metrics:\n* WMC: a class complexity measure, see {% jdoc java::lang.java.metrics.JavaMetrics#WEIGHED_METHOD_COUNT %}\n* ATFD: a measure of how much data external data the class uses, see {% jdoc java::lang.java.metrics.JavaMetrics#ACCESS_TO_FOREIGN_DATA %}\n* TCC: a measure of how tightly related the methods are, see {% jdoc java::lang.java.metrics.JavaMetrics#TIGHT_CLASS_COHESION %}\n\nThe rule identifies a god class by looking for classes which have all of the following properties:\n* High WMC\n* High ATFD\n* Low TCC\n\nSee also the reference:\n\nMichele Lanza and Radu Marinescu. *Object-Oriented Metrics in Practice:\nUsing Software Metrics to Characterize, Evaluate, and Improve the Design\nof Object-Oriented Systems.* Springer, Berlin, 1 edition, October 2006. Page 80.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Design",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Design"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CyclomaticComplexity",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "The class 'BibEntry' has a total cyclomatic complexity of 245 (highest 80)."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nThe complexity of methods directly affects maintenance costs and readability. Concentrating too much decisional logic\nin a single method makes its behaviour hard to read and change.\n\nCyclomatic complexity assesses the complexity of a method by counting the number of decision points in a method,\nplus one for the method entry. Decision points are places where the control flow jumps to another place in the\nprogram. As such, they include all control flow statements, such as `if`, `while`, `for`, and `case`. For more\ndetails on the calculation, see the documentation {% jdoc java::lang.java.metrics.JavaMetrics#CYCLO %}.\n\nGenerally, numbers ranging from 1-4 denote low complexity, 5-7 denote moderate complexity, 8-10 denote\nhigh complexity, and 11+ is very high complexity. By default, this rule reports methods with a complexity >= 10.\nAdditionally, classes with many methods of moderate complexity get reported as well once the total of their\nmethods' complexities reaches 80, even if none of the methods was directly reported.\n\nReported methods should be broken down into several smaller methods. Reported classes should probably be broken down\ninto subcomponents.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_design.html#cyclomaticcomplexity",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nThe complexity of methods directly affects maintenance costs and readability. Concentrating too much decisional logic\nin a single method makes its behaviour hard to read and change.\n\nCyclomatic complexity assesses the complexity of a method by counting the number of decision points in a method,\nplus one for the method entry. Decision points are places where the control flow jumps to another place in the\nprogram. As such, they include all control flow statements, such as `if`, `while`, `for`, and `case`. For more\ndetails on the calculation, see the documentation {% jdoc java::lang.java.metrics.JavaMetrics#CYCLO %}.\n\nGenerally, numbers ranging from 1-4 denote low complexity, 5-7 denote moderate complexity, 8-10 denote\nhigh complexity, and 11+ is very high complexity. By default, this rule reports methods with a complexity >= 10.\nAdditionally, classes with many methods of moderate complexity get reported as well once the total of their\nmethods' complexities reaches 80, even if none of the methods was directly reported.\n\nReported methods should be broken down into several smaller methods. Reported classes should probably be broken down\ninto subcomponents.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Design",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Design"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ExcessivePublicCount",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "This class has 96 public methods and attributes; current threshold is 45."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nClasses with large numbers of public methods and attributes require disproportionate testing efforts\nsince combinational side effects grow rapidly and increase risk. Refactoring these classes into\nsmaller ones not only increases testability and reliability but also allows new variations to be\ndeveloped easily.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_design.html#excessivepubliccount",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nClasses with large numbers of public methods and attributes require disproportionate testing efforts\nsince combinational side effects grow rapidly and increase risk. Refactoring these classes into\nsmaller ones not only increases testability and reliability but also allows new variations to be\ndeveloped easily.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Design",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Design"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "TooManyMethods",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "This class has too many methods, consider refactoring it."
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "\nA class with too many methods is probably a good suspect for refactoring, in order to reduce its\ncomplexity and find a way to have more fine grained objects.\n        "
              },
              "helpUri": "https://docs.pmd-code.org/snapshot/pmd_rules_java_design.html#toomanymethods",
              "help": {
                "text": "\nA class with too many methods is probably a good suspect for refactoring, in order to reduce its\ncomplexity and find a way to have more fine grained objects.\n        "
              },
              "properties": {
                "ruleset": "Design",
                "priority": 3,
                "tags": [
                  "Design"
                ]
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              }
            },
            {
